146 TRINVMM VS. [ACT 111.

Stasimus poses as a moneyed gentleman who can lend a friend a large sum—yet the land they are in danger of losing is all that keeps him and his master from starvation.

Exit Stasimus to the Forum, i. e. to the right.

SCENE 3 (729—819). The previous scene has shewn how great the difficulty about the dowry is. Now we are shewn how Callicles tries to surmount it. He has gone (v. 614) to consult Megaronides. They enter in conversation; Megaronides finally suggests getting a man to pretend he has come from Charmides, and thereby secretly conveying part of the hidden treasure as the girl's dowry. But this plan when put into execution (Act IV.) only complicates matters.

Metre—Iambic Trimeters.

Ritschl assumes a gap here, containing lines spoken by Callicles to the effect—‘What I don’t know is whether to let the marriage go forward now or wait until Charmides returns.’ But if we suppose that Megaronides continues almost without listening to what Callicles says, perhaps no gap need be assumed. And this is Leo’s view.
